{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1bed20e0-276c-4358-9e60-35eb77dcc1f6","content":"Here's how to collect a trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```powershell\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace`:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n$env:PATH += \";$env:USERPROFILE\\.dotnet\\tools\"\n```\n\n**3. Find your process and collect:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```powershell\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-file>.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** with Visual Studio (open the `.nettrace` file) or [PerfView](https://github.com/microsoft/perfview). You can also convert to Speedscope format:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails (no SDK in the container), download the standalone `dotnet-trace` from the [.NET diagnostics releases](https://github.com/dotnet/diagnostics) or copy it in via `kubectl cp`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2379b8b2-e900-4866-bb74-2ed6a9885f31","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to collect a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I should provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":401,"requestId":"9435:170FAA:1907DA8:1C44B08:69E81D16"},"id":"035517d3-937e-409d-aa45-f09aff750c10","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:58:07.314Z","parentId":"9a85286c-ebdf-4523-a5ff-2130c834d734"}
